Investigation of volatile organic metabolites in lung cancer pleural effusions by solid-phase microextraction and gas chromatography/mass spectrometry.
H. Liu, H. Wang, C. Li, L. Wang, Z. Pan, L. Wang
J. Chromatogr. B Analyt. Technol. Biomed. Life Sci. 2014 Jan;945-946:53-9.

In this context, 2-ethylhexan-1-ol is identified as a metabolite that exhibits significantly higher levels in malignant pleural effusions compared to benign ones. This suggests that 2-ethylhexan-1-ol could serve as a potential biomarker for differentiating malignant pleural effusions, indicating its relevance in the diagnosis of lung cancers. The study highlights the importance of analyzing volatile organic metabolites in pleural effusions for cancer detection.

In this context, 2-ethylhexan-1-ol and cyclohexanone are both identified as urinary biomarkers for lung cancer. Cyclohexanone is linked to metabolic conditions associated with advanced cancer, while 2-ethylhexan-1-ol shows a significant increase in cancerous cell headspace compared to controls. Both compounds are considered potential candidates for differentiating malignant from benign pleural effusions, indicating a shared relevance in cancer diagnostics.
